<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post223640"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Shadowfrost</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">did Ragefire the hard way</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Jun 2002<br>
	Location: <br>
	Posts: 1099</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b>Recurring idea on PC</b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">I accept that many clerics don't <i>want</i> changes to the priest classes and feel that things are fine as they are... I can understand that view, but I don't think that hoping to continue the status quo is realistic.  Druids and shamans are pushing hard for upgrades, and my belief is that SOE may well listen to them sympathetically.<br />
<br />
I think we need to get together as a class and agree on the direction in which we want to take clerics in the event that this happens.  Last time the other priest classes got big increases, clerics were very much caught on the hop - there was no consensus on what we wanted, so SoE chose a way forward for us and the result was the cleric hammer.  Personally I feel that the whole series of events was a disaster for clerics from beginning to end.<br />
<br />
This time, I'm hoping to achieve a clear consensus from clerics on what we want.<br />
<br />
Boanerges has made the case for increased cleric damage output, and that's certainly a realistic way forward.  I agree with him, but I also feel that (a) if the healing upgrades for other priests are relatively large, tinkering with DPS may be insufficient, and (b) it would be nice to have an alternative for us to debate as well.<br />
<br />
The most frequently occurring suggestion on the Priest's Covenant, particularly from non-clerics, seems to be to add crowd control to the cleric spell lineup.  I was amazed to see how many druids and shamans think that clerics ought to be able to mezz!<br />
<br />
I suspect that there's an element of NIMBYism to that attitude.  I think that some priests like the idea of cleric crowd control because then questions like cleric slow, cleric haste, cleric snare etc. don't arise and their own skillset retains its full value relative to clerics.  I imagine it's much more comfortable for them to offer  abilities which previously belonged to bards and chanters than to offer abilities they see as "theirs!"<br />
<br />
Personally I don't believe clerics should be able to mezz.  I think that particular idea is a bridge too far - but I'd certainly be interested to hear from any clerics who think otherwise.<br />
<br />
I do believe that it's worth building on the crowd control avenues which clerics already possess, though.  One alternative that's going through my head at the moment is this:<br />
<br />
<b>Crowd Controlling Cleric model</b><br />
<br />
1.  Pacification line changes:  Either hugely increase the duration of Paci, or increase it somewhat and reduce the mana cost.  Consider adding an AA which would further reduce the chances of aggro on a paci resist.  Consider adding an upgrade to Wake of Tranquillity (AE pacify).<br />
<br />
2.  Atone changes:  Add a success/failure message to Atone.  Hugely increase the chances of success for Atone, although it still shouldn't be guaranteed.  Change Atone to a beneficial spell like Paci, so that monsters don't automatically aggro on a resist.<br />
<br />
3.  Root changes:  Add a more reliable fast-cast root.<br />
<br />
The result I'm aiming for with the model is a cleric who can pull like a bard, and also use the root/paci/atone combination to cope with adds.  (You'd deal with an add by rooting it, pacifying it, then atoning; hopefully when root wears off, the add would simply wander back to its spawn spot).<br />
<br />
I'm interested to know if anyone likes this idea?</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">__________________<br>
Shadowfrost<br />
<br />
<i>...there's just too many classes for not enough roles. Most of the time class balancing involves robbing Peter to pay Paul. There's really no way around it... <br />
<br />
...Honestly I think that having shaman/druid/cleric all being able to heal more or less the same is good for game balance, as long as the rest of the classes abilities balance out to make them equally desirable.</i><br />
<br />
 - Rytan the Wyrmlord, EQ "Spell Guy"</font></p></p>
	<p></p>
